[1] Cholera - Angola
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New York Times [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/20/world/africa/20angola.html?_r=1&oref=slogin>

Angola is suffering its worst outbreak of cholera in more than a
decade, recording 554 deaths and 12 052 cases in just over 2 months,
according to Doctors Without Borders.
The disease has spread unusually fast, even for Africa, where cholera
epidemics are common and often hard to control, said Stephan
Goetghebuer, an operational coordinator for the organization. It has
set up 8 clinics in Angola to treat the sick and plans to open more.
"The severity of this outbreak is something remarkable, really rare,"
Mr. Goetghebuer said in a phone interview from Brussels. Initially
concentrated in the capital, Luanda, the disease has spread to 3
other cities within a radius of about 250 miles.
In 2005, cholera swept through West Africa, striking 20 000 people in
Guinea Bissau alone, Mr. Goetghebuer said. [So far in 2006], aid
workers have fought outbreaks in Zambia, Zimbabwe, Malawi and
southern Sudan. But Angola has largely been spared cholera outbreaks
since 1995. That may have lessened the population's immunity and
helps explain the rapid spread of the disease since the first case
was reported on 13 Feb 2006, Mr. Goetghebuer said.
Luanda's slums are a perfect breeding ground for cholera, which is
typically transmitted through contaminated food or water. In the
poorest sections, latrines are rare and children play in open
trenches that carry waste, said Richard Veerman, who is organizing
the response by Doctors Without Borders.
Mr. Goetghebuer said, "The hygiene is terrible -- terrible, even
compared to other places in Africa."
[Byline: Sharon LaFraniere]
--
