[8] Cholera - Tanzania (Dar es Salaam, Zanzibar)
Date: Wed, 19 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/Africa/News/0,,2-11-1447_1918933,00.html>

A month-long outbreak of cholera has killed 21 people and stricken
253 in mainland Tanzania and the semiautonomous Zanzibar archipelago,
the country's health officials said on Wednesday.
A spokesperson for the Dar es Salaam city council, Gaston Makwembe,
said 12 people have died in the past 4 days, and 115 were taken to
hospitals in Tanzania's commercial capital.
He said 9 people have died of the disease in Zanzibar in the past
month, and 137 cases have been reported. Zanzibar's health minister
Sultan Mugheiry said those infected were [placed] in special
government camps in an attempt to curb the disease.
[During March 2006], Zanzibar banned the sale of food and juice on
the street, and closed some local restaurants in attempts to stop the
disease from spreading.
Mugheiry said: "We are confident that the situation is under control."
Cholera has erupted across East Africa, after heavy rains in the region.
[Byline: Ali Sultan]
--
