[9] Cholera - Tanzania (Zanzibar)
Date: Wed, 19 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: TodayOnline.com [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/113379.asp>

At least 9 people have died of cholera in the past month on
Tanzania's Zanzibar archipelago, officials said, appealing for
improved sanitation to help fight the outbreak. At least 5
additional fatalities have been reported since authorities in late
Mar 2006 gave a death toll of 4 and more than 137 people have been
taken ill by the waterborne disease, health minister Sultan Mohamed
Mugheiry said Tue, 18 Apr 2006.
"We still have the cholera problem in both Unguja and Pemba islands
and I appeal to the public to use boiled water and keep their
environment clean," he said, adding that a ban on street sales of
sugar cane juice remains in effect. Despite the additional deaths,
Mugheiry said the health situation "seems to be stable" on Zanzibar,
which is home to about a million people.

Cholera has repeatedly hit Zanzibar in recent years, with the last
severe outbreak recorded in 1997, when more than 1100 people were
taken ill by the disease and at least 124 died.
--
